# Top-level requires

All `require` and `require_relative` statements belong at the top of the file.
Do not place them inside method bodies, blocks, or callbacks.

```ruby
# BAD: lazy require inside a block
BuiltinCommand.new(desc: "Update deps") do |args:, context:|
  require "dev/deps"
  require "dev/deps/resolver"
  # ...
end

# GOOD: requires at the top of the file
require "dev/deps"
require "dev/deps/resolver"

BuiltinCommand.new(desc: "Update deps") do |args:, context:|
  # ...
end
```

Lazy loading is intentional in some frameworks (e.g., Rails autoloading), but
in this codebase all dependencies are loaded eagerly at file scope.
